column2: Description of the criteria
Children under the legal minimum working age are not employed
Minors do not engage in dangerous work
If children help their families, it does not interfere with their access to education
Workers can leave freely
Workers’ spouses and children are not required to work
Identity papers, payments, or other properties are not withheld to force workers to remain at work
Workers earn at least the local minimum wage or industry standard wage, whichever is higher
In the case of piecemeal or collective work, workers earn at least the industry standard wage
Workers have access to clean drinking water on site
Toilets and handwashing facilities are on site and located away from water bodies
Workers have protective equipment and safe usage training
Pregnant women are prohibited from dangerous work
Primary and protected forests have not been cut down or degraded
Clearing of new land for coffee has been authorized with the appropriate local permit
Effluent waste is treated to prevent contamination of water bodies
Coffee processing byproducts (e.g., pulp, husks) are recycled
There is no hunting or trapping of protected species
Diverse shade trees on coffee farms are present
Erosion control measures are taken on sloped areas
Mulch, compost, and/or cover crops are used to increase soil organic matter
Fertilizer application is informed by recent soil testing
Water use for processing and irrigation is tracked
Water consumption is at best practice levels or in the process of being reduced
There are buffer zones around any water bodies on site
There is no storage or application of any product that contains an ingredient present on the most recent List of Banned Pesticides
Chemicals are stored in a place that is secure, dry, well-ventilated, and never used for storing food or coffee
Empty containers are disposed of safely
Pests, diseases and weeds are controlled using an integrated management approach
Scouting is practiced to monitor pest and disease levels
Chemical spraying is used only as a last resort
Coffee farming families have a standard of living that is above the United Nation's extreme poverty line of $2/day (based on PPI* factor)
Coffee farming families have a standard of living that is above the United Nation's poverty line of $3/day (based on PPI* factor)
Pricing is open and competitive
Receipts are given and signs are posted
Farm yields are at local best practice levels
Trees are pruned or rejuvenated regularly
Producer has access to processing infrastructure and markets that reward quality
Coffee is dried and stored so as to prevent mold and ochratoxin formation
Producer receives technical assistance on different topics or has recently completed a technical assistance program
Producer has a savings account
Producer has access to credit at reasonable interest rates
Producer is not over-indebted
Records of production/inventory, sales, expenses, and other activities are maintained and reconciled
